sudo tc qdisc del dev eno1 root 2>/dev/null

# Changing the queue size
## Test 1: cwnd_128_178_122_39_46844.png (5GB)
- sudo tc qdisc add dev eno1 root tbf rate 100mbit burst 64kbit limit 150000
- RTT: 0.150 ~ 0.256 
- 0.256 * 100 Mbps == 25600 bits must be in flight to utilize the pipe 100%
  (while waiting for the ACK, this is the maximum amount of data that you could send)

- queue size is 150,000 bytes which is approximately 100 packets
- so to send 5GB, assuming that the MTU is 1500 bytes, you need 3,333,333 packets

## Test 2: cwnd_128_178_122_39_44702.png (5GB)
- sudo tc qdisc add dev eno1 root tbf rate 100mbit burst 64kbit limit 300000

## Test 3: cwnd_128_178_122_39_33140.png (5GB)
- sudo tc qdisc add dev eno1 root tbf rate 100mbit burst 64kbit limit 450000

Increasing the queue size does not solve the plateu issue. This is because
when the queue size is big, RTT will be longer (it takes longer for a packet to exit the queue). And since RTT ts longer, this means that the time we receive ACK will be longer as well. Since TCP only increases cwnd when it receives an ACK, this causes the plateau as shown in the figures above (**or maybe it could be caused by the receiver's recv_buffer being full (flow control) and the receiver sending recv_wnd == 0, telling the sender to stop**).

![alt text](cc_fc.png)

Since RTT is around 0.144 ~ 0.242ms, BDP is around 25600 bits (3200 bytes), it might be better to try around with a queue size that is **2 to 4 times the BDP**. 

